{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502225"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:41:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:41:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1838"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1838"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.25,0.03,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1838"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47439"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1838"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1838"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32152"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"3884"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12421"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47439"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to her post-operative clinic after undergoing a wide local excision and sentinel node biopsy for a 2 cm right breast lump. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. The histology report shows a grade III invasive ductal carcinoma which is oestrogen receptor positive, progesterone receptor positive, and HER2 negative. No metastases were found in the three sentinel lymph nodes that were excised.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In this patient, which one of the following will have the greatest negative impact on prognosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oestrogen receptor status","Progesterone receptor status","HER2 status","Tumour size","Tumour grade"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOf the factors listed, the \u003Cstrong\u003Egrade III histology\u003C/strong\u003E of the tumour will have the greatest negative impact on prognosis. Histological grade is the most important prognostic factor for breast cancer recurrence and survival in patients with small, node-negative tumours. Higher grade tumours (grade III) are more aggressive and associated with shorter disease-free and overall survival compared to lower grade tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOestrogen receptor positivity\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eprogesterone receptor positivity\u003C/strong\u003E are actually associated with a better prognosis in breast cancer. Hormone receptor-positive tumours tend to be lower grade, slower growing, and more responsive to endocrine therapy compared to hormone receptor-negative tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHER2 negativity\u003C/strong\u003E is also associated with a better prognosis compared to HER2 positivity. HER2-positive tumours tend to be higher grade and have a more aggressive clinical course. However, the development of HER2-targeted therapies has significantly improved outcomes for patients with HER2-positive disease compared to previous.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E2 cm tumour size\u003C/strong\u003E places this patient\u0027s cancer in the T1c category, which has a better prognosis than larger tumours. Tumour size is an important prognostic factor, but in this case, the high histological grade will have a greater influence on the patient\u0027s risk of recurrence and survival.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Histological grade is the most important prognostic factor for breast cancer recurrence and survival in patients with small, node-negative tumours.","Oestrogen and progesterone receptor positivity are associated with a better prognosis in breast cancer.","HER2 positivity is associated with a worse prognosis in breast cancer"],"references":["Foukakis T, Bergh J. Prognostic and predictive factors in early, non-metastatic breast cancer. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/prognostic-and-predictive-factors-in-early-non-metastatic-breast-cancer","Stankov A, Bargallo-Rocha JE, Silvio A\u00d1, Ramirez MT, Stankova-Ninova K, Meneses-Garcia A. Prognostic factors and recurrence in breast cancer: experience at the national cancer institute of Mexico. ISRN Oncol. 2012;2012:825258. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3399427/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32152"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1838"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32152"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-23T16:53:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-01T21:01:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1838"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47439"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","sy